<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1370,2007]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<bibRefCitation author="Gapasin, D. P." box="[199,374,1478,1503]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref48938" refString="Gapasin, D. P. (1972) A generic revision and higher classification of the family Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) [Ph. D. thesis]. The Pennsylvania State University, Pennsylvania, U. S. A., 339 pp." type="book" year="1972">Gapasin (1972)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, I. P." box="[433,583,1478,1503]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref50178" refString="Smith, I. P. (1994) Systematics of Pterogramma Spuler (Diptera: Sphaeroceridae) [MSc thesis]. The University of Guelph, Guelph, ON, Canada, 402 pp." type="book" year="1994">Smith (1994)</bibRefCitation>
both redescribed 
<taxonomicName box="[789,946,1478,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borgmeieri">
<emphasis box="[789,946,1478,1502]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">A. borgmeieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Duda, O." box="[1065,1210,1478,1503]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="74 - 76" refId="ref48852" refString="Duda, O. (1924) Aptilotella borgmeieri ♂, eine neue flugellose Borboride (Dipt.) aus Brasilien. Natuurhistorisch Maandblad, Maastricht, 13, 74 - 76." type="journal article" year="1924">Duda (1924)</bibRefCitation>
and specimens that originated from “a long series in 
<collectingRegion box="[523,636,1514,1539]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
[MZSP]” collected by F. Plaumann on an unknown date at 
<quantity box="[1309,1436,1514,1539]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="450.0" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="300.0">300–600 m</quantity>
in Nova Teutonia (abbreviated NT), 
<collectingCountry box="[559,631,1550,1575]" name="Brazil" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. The structural characters recorded from this specimen by 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, I. P." box="[1287,1436,1550,1575]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref50178" refString="Smith, I. P. (1994) Systematics of Pterogramma Spuler (Diptera: Sphaeroceridae) [MSc thesis]. The University of Guelph, Guelph, ON, Canada, 402 pp." type="book" year="1994">Smith (1994)</bibRefCitation>
are inconsistent with Duda’s description, including a reduced orbital bristle and double rows of interfrontal setae. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gapasin, D. P." box="[151,326,1622,1647]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref48938" refString="Gapasin, D. P. (1972) A generic revision and higher classification of the family Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) [Ph. D. thesis]. The Pennsylvania State University, Pennsylvania, U. S. A., 339 pp." type="book" year="1972">Gapasin (1972)</bibRefCitation>
examined a single female from the NT series and illustrates a pair of bean-shaped spermathecae. No such spermathecal morphology is known in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1924" box="[762,880,1659,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[762,880,1659,1683]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Aptilotella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is possible that 
<bibRefCitation author="Gapasin, D. P." box="[1098,1273,1658,1683]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref48938" refString="Gapasin, D. P. (1972) A generic revision and higher classification of the family Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) [Ph. D. thesis]. The Pennsylvania State University, Pennsylvania, U. S. A., 339 pp." type="book" year="1972">Gapasin (1972)</bibRefCitation>
illustrated the deflated paired spermathecae, while the third spermatheca was either lost or overlooked. The NT series originated from Serra Geral, a mountain range separate from the Serra Da Mantiqueira Mountains in which the 
<typeStatus box="[1268,1316,1731,1755]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,305,1766,1790]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borgmeieri">
<emphasis box="[151,305,1766,1790]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">A. borgmeieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is situated. Because of uncertainty about the identity of the species described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gapasin, D. P." box="[1215,1389,1766,1791]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref48938" refString="Gapasin, D. P. (1972) A generic revision and higher classification of the family Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) [Ph. D. thesis]. The Pennsylvania State University, Pennsylvania, U. S. A., 339 pp." type="book" year="1972">Gapasin (1972)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, I. P." box="[151,301,1802,1827]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref50178" refString="Smith, I. P. (1994) Systematics of Pterogramma Spuler (Diptera: Sphaeroceridae) [MSc thesis]. The University of Guelph, Guelph, ON, Canada, 402 pp." type="book" year="1994">Smith (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, their notes are not reflected in the redescription below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1370,2007]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1436,151,608]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,339,1838,1863]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Description.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[492,581,1838,1863]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
. Head ground color dark brown. Frons black, shining; with a pair of narrow, parallel grey stripes. Ocelli absent; ocellar bristle three quarters the length of frons. Interfrontal setae minute, in two or three pairs. Several pairs of orbital setulae present. Orbital and vertical bristles absent. Face and gena shining; lunule, clypeus, and gena black. Body black, shining. Scutum twice wider than long; sparsely microtrichose. Scutellum approximately twice wider than long. Pleuron black. Legs brown; tarsi light brown; mid tibia with two anterodorsal bristles. Wings absent. Abdomen with large syntergite approximately the length of the other tergites combined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,608]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Terminalia.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Duda, O." box="[340,482,223,248]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="74 - 76" refId="ref48852" refString="Duda, O. (1924) Aptilotella borgmeieri ♂, eine neue flugellose Borboride (Dipt.) aus Brasilien. Natuurhistorisch Maandblad, Maastricht, 13, 74 - 76." type="journal article" year="1924">Duda (1924)</bibRefCitation>
vaguely noted synsternite 6+7 and the epandrium, but did not describe any genitalic characters or dissect any specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1378,295,320]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,608]" box="[199,1378,295,320]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,364,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Type material.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3311767425" box="[371,1378,295,320]" collectionCode="MZSP" collectorName="Petropolis, T." country="Brazil" location="BRAZIL" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" specimenCount="1" specimenCount-male="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus box="[371,475,295,320]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Holotype</typeStatus>
<specimenCount box="[482,503,296,319]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
(
<collectionCode box="[518,593,295,320]" country="Brazil" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/9yp6-zxp9" name="Sao Paulo, Museu de Zoologia da Universidade de Sao Paulo" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="Museum">MZSP</collectionCode>
, not examined and probably lost). 
